# Migrating {{ tenant.name }} to your own servers

This bundle makes {{ tenant.name }} ({{ external_host }}) **self-hosted**: you run
Pinpoint 311 on infrastructure you control, with all of your data, and the state
no longer hosts or has any access to it.

**What's in this bundle**
- `docker-compose.yml` — the full standalone stack (Postgres, Redis, backend,
  worker, frontend, Caddy with automatic TLS).
- `.env` — your configuration and the keys your instance was using. **Rotate
  every secret here after you're live.**
- `Caddyfile` — edge routing + TLS for your domain.
{% if includes_data -%}
- `data/dump.sql` — a full dump of your database (all service requests, users,
  settings — PII included, still encrypted with your existing `SECRET_KEY`).
- `data/uploads.tar.gz` — your uploaded files/attachments.
{%- else -%}
- (No data snapshot was included — generate one with the commands in Step 2.)
{%- endif %}

## Step 1 — Stand up a host
Provision a Linux VM you control with Docker + Docker Compose. Copy this bundle
onto it and `cd` into the folder.

## Step 2 — Bring up the database, then load your data
```bash
docker compose up -d db
{% if includes_data -%}
# Restore the included dump into the fresh database:
docker compose exec -T db psql -U township -d {{ tenant.db_name or 'pp311' }} < data/dump.sql
{%- else -%}
# If you didn't get a data snapshot, the state operator can produce one from the
# managed host (they have the resource references):
#   docker exec pp311-{{ tenant.slug }}-db-1 pg_dump -U township {{ tenant.db_name or 'pp311' }} > dump.sql
# then copy dump.sql here and:
#   docker compose exec -T db psql -U township -d {{ tenant.db_name or 'pp311' }} < dump.sql
{%- endif %}
```
{% if includes_data -%}
Then restore your uploaded files:
```bash
tar xzf data/uploads.tar.gz -C ./uploads
```
{%- endif %}

## Step 3 — Bring up the whole stack
```bash
docker compose up -d
docker compose ps        # all healthy?
curl -f https://{{ external_host }}/api/health/quick
```

## Step 4 — Cut over DNS
Point `{{ external_host }}` (or your own domain) at this host's public IP. Caddy
issues a TLS certificate automatically on first request.

## Step 5 — Rotate secrets
Everything in `.env` was generated by the state. Rotate now:
- `SECRET_KEY` (see the app's key-rotation runbook — rotating it re-wraps
  encrypted data; do this before going public).
- Every external API key you own (maps, AI, SMS, SSO, SMTP, …).

## Step 6 — Tell the state to retire the managed instance
Once you've verified you're live and correct on your own infra, ask your state
program office to **decommission** the managed copy. Until they do, your data is
retained on the platform (read-only) as a safety net — nothing is deleted.

You are now fully independent: separate database, separate keys, your servers.
